## Context

RDJ-26561 R&R (tracker 0274), remark R1-06 (with folded footnote R1-08). The
referee: the corpus's grey literature apparently excludes documents from
national institutions — government and parliamentary reports, economic
analysis councils, central bank communications (cites Campiglio, Deyris,
Romelli & Scalisi 2025, "Warning words in a warming world", European Economic
Review, on central bank communication). Why? What is the justification? Was
incorporating them considered, to broaden coverage and multilingual scope?

## Relevant files

- `deliverables/data-paper/data-paper.qmd` — Sources (2.1) and Quality/Biases
  sections
- Phase-1 source scripts (`catalog_*`) — the actual source-inclusion decisions
- `docs/braindump-2026-03-18.md` — may hold prior scoping reasoning

## Actions

1. Reconstruct the actual scoping rationale for grey-literature sources (what
   was included, why national-institution documents fall outside).
2. Write the justification into the paper's sources/limitations discussion —
   scope boundary stated as a design decision, with the extension path named
   as future work (incorporating them for real is a major corpus expansion;
   author call, likely out of scope for this revision).
3. Consider citing the referee's central-bank-communication example as the
   pointer for that future direction. Read-before-cite norm applies.

